*[#darkblue] <i>Centralized Workflow\n<img:images/img_9.png>
**[#lightblue] <i><color #blac><size:12>Overview
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Utilizes a Single Shared Repository
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>All developers interact with a central repository.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Linear Development Flow
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Follows a straightforward commit and update cycle.
***[#a] <b><i><color #black><size:12>[[https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/comparing-workflows Centralized workflow]] article of attlasian
**[#lightblue] <i><color #blac><size:12>Main Components\n<img:images/img_9.png{scale=.84}>
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Master Branch
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Mainline branch representing the official project history.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Commits and Updates
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Developers commit changes directly to the master branch.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Collaboration and Communication
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Developers coordinate changes and updates through direct commits.
**[#lightblue] <i><color #blac><size:12>Workflow Characteristics
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Simplicity and Linearity
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Easy-to-understand, sequential approach for development.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Version Control
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Tracks changes and maintains a linear history.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Limitations in Collaboration
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Lacks features for concurrent, collaborative development.
**[#lightblue] <i><color #blac><size:12>Process Flow
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Clone Central Repository
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Developers clone the central repository to their local machines.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Make Changes Locally
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Changes and updates made within the local repository.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Commit to Central Repository
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Developers commit changes directly to the master branch.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Pull Updates
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Periodically pull changes made by others from the central repository.
**[#lightblue] <i><color #blac><size:12>Advantages
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Straightforward and Understandable
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Easy for new users to grasp and follow.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Clear Versioning
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Provides a linear history of changes.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Centralized Control
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Offers centralized oversight and management of the codebase.
**[#lightblue] <i><color #blac><size:12>Considerations
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Limited Collaboration Features
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Restricts concurrent, collaborative work.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Risk of Conflicting Changes\n<img:images/img_12.png{scale=.8}>
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Direct commits to master may lead to conflicts.
***[#green] <b><i><color #white><size:12>Central Repository Dependency
****[#yellow] <i><color #black><size:12>Heavily reliant on the central repository's availability.
@endmindmap
